## Markdown Extensions

The following Markdown extensions are available beyond standard CommonMark:

### Tables

Standard GFM (GitHub Flavoured Markdown) tables are supported:

```markdown
| Column A | Column B | Column C |
|----------|----------|----------|
| Cell     | Cell     | Cell     |
```

### Task Lists

```markdown
- [x] Done item
- [ ] Pending item
```

### Footnotes

```markdown
Here is a claim.[^1]

[^1]: Source or clarification.
```

### Code Blocks with Syntax Highlighting

Fenced code blocks with a language identifier get syntax highlighting:

````markdown
```typescript
function greet(name: string): string {
  return `Hello, ${name}`;
}
```
````

Supported languages include: `typescript`, `javascript`, `python`, `bash`, `yaml`, `json`, `css`, `html`, `markdown`, and many others.

Add a filename by appending it after the language:

````markdown
```typescript title="src/utils/greet.ts"
function greet(name: string): string {
  return `Hello, ${name}`;
}
```
````

### Callouts / Admonitions

Use the following syntax for callout blocks:

{% if framework == "astro" %}
Callouts use a custom `<Callout>` component imported in MDX files. In plain Markdown, use the blockquote convention:

```markdown
> [!NOTE]
> This is a note callout.

> [!WARNING]
> This is a warning callout.

> [!TIP]
> This is a tip callout.
```

In MDX files:

```mdx
import Callout from '@/components/content/Callout.astro';

<Callout type="warning">
  This action cannot be undone.
</Callout>
```
{% elif framework == "hugo" %}
Use Hugo shortcodes:

{% raw %}
```
{{< callout type="note" >}}
This is a note.
{{< /callout >}}

{{< callout type="warning" >}}
This is a warning.
{{< /callout >}}
```
{% endraw %}
{% else %}
Use blockquote convention (transformed to styled callouts by the Markdown plugin):

```markdown
> [!NOTE]
> This is a note callout.

> [!WARNING]
> This is a warning callout.
```
{% endif %}

Available types: `note`, `tip`, `warning`, `danger`, `info`

## Using Components in Content

{% if framework == "astro" %}
Files with a `.mdx` extension can import and use Astro or framework components directly:

```mdx
---
title: "My Page"
description: "..."
---

import VideoEmbed from '@/components/content/VideoEmbed.astro';
import DataTable from '@/components/content/DataTable.astro';

Standard Markdown content here.

<VideoEmbed id="dQw4w9WgXcQ" title="Demo video" />

More Markdown content.

<DataTable
  headers={["Name", "Value"]}
  rows={[["Alpha", "1"], ["Beta", "2"]]}
/>
```

Use `.mdx` when you need components; use `.md` for pure Markdown content.
{% elif framework == "nextjs-static" %}
MDX files can import React components:

```mdx
---
title: "My Page"
description: "..."
---

import { Callout } from '@/components/content/Callout';
import { CodeSandbox } from '@/components/content/CodeSandbox';

Standard Markdown content.

<Callout type="tip">
  Use MDX when you need interactive or styled components inside content.
</Callout>
```
{% elif framework == "hugo" %}
Hugo uses shortcodes for reusable content snippets. They live in `layouts/shortcodes/`:

{% raw %}
```
{{< youtube id="dQw4w9WgXcQ" title="Demo video" >}}

{{< figure src="./diagram.png" alt="System architecture diagram" caption="Figure 1: System overview" >}}
```

Shortcodes accept named parameters and can include inner content:

```
{{< callout type="warning" >}}
  Content here is passed as `.Inner`.
{{< /callout >}}
```
{% endraw %}
{% elif framework == "eleventy" %}
Nunjucks shortcodes registered in `.eleventy.js` can be used in content templates:

```
{% raw %}{% callout "warning" %}
  Content here.
{% endcallout %}{% endraw %}
```

For more complex interactivity, use web components that are self-contained in `src/assets/js/`.
{% endif %}

## SEO Metadata

### Page Title

The `title` frontmatter field is used in:
- The browser `<title>` tag (format: `{title} - {{ display_name }}`)
- The `<h1>` heading (on most layouts)
- `og:title` Open Graph tag
- `twitter:title` Twitter card tag

Guidelines:
- 50-60 characters including the site name suffix
- Include the primary keyword near the beginning
- Be specific and descriptive - avoid generic titles like "Home" or "Overview"

### Meta Description

The `description` frontmatter field is used in:
- The `<meta name="description">` tag
- `og:description` Open Graph tag
- `twitter:description` Twitter card tag

Guidelines:
- 120-160 characters
- Write for humans first - this appears in search results and link previews
- Summarise what the reader will learn or accomplish, not just what the page is about
- Include a natural keyword or phrase

### Open Graph Images

Set a custom OG image in frontmatter:

```yaml
ogImage: "./og-image.png"
```

If not set, the site's default OG image from `public/og-image.png` is used.

OG image specifications:
- Dimensions: 1200x630px
- Format: PNG or JPG
- File size: under 1MB
- Include the page title as text in the image for recognisability in link previews

### Structured Data

{% if site_type == "blog" %}
Blog posts automatically include `Article` schema markup. To add FAQ structured data to a post:

```yaml
faq:
  - question: "What is this?"
    answer: "It is a thing."
  - question: "How does it work?"
    answer: "Very well, thank you."
```
{% elif site_type == "docs" %}
Documentation pages include `TechArticle` schema markup automatically.
{% endif %}

Additional structured data can be added via a `schema` frontmatter field accepting a JSON-LD object.

## Image Handling

### Images in `src/assets/` (processed)

Reference images using a relative path from the content file:

```markdown
![Alt text describing the image](./screenshot.png)
```

The build pipeline will:
- Generate multiple sizes (400w, 800w, 1200w) for responsive `srcset`
- Convert to WebP with PNG/JPG fallback
- Add `width` and `height` attributes to prevent layout shift
- Apply lazy loading to images that are not in the initial viewport

### Images in `public/` (unprocessed)

Reference by absolute path from the site root:

```markdown
![Site logo](/logo.png)
```

Use `public/` only when the image needs a stable, predictable URL (e.g., an OG image referenced in email newsletters or external metadata).

### Alt Text

Write alt text that describes the image content for someone who cannot see it:

| Situation | Example |
|-----------|---------|
| Screenshot with UI | "The settings panel showing notification toggles for email and push alerts" |
| Chart or graph | "Line chart showing weekly active users growing from 1,200 in January to 4,500 in June" |
| Logo | "{{ display_name }} logo" |
| Decorative image | `alt=""` (empty) |
| Image containing important text | Include the text verbatim in the alt attribute |

## Writing Style

- Use second person ("you") when addressing the reader directly
- Write in active voice: "Click Save" not "The Save button should be clicked"
- Use present tense for descriptions: "The panel shows..." not "The panel will show..."
- Keep sentences under 25 words where possible
- Define acronyms on first use: "Content Management System (CMS)"
- Use numbered lists for sequential steps; use bullet lists for unordered items
